# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arky-vaughan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The **1932 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1932.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 25, with the Chicago Cubs and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 29th World Series on September 28 and ended with Game 4 on October 2.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The Yankees swept the Cubs in four games, capturing their fourth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1928.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the St.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League, the Brooklyn Robins reverted to their 1913 name, the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The 1932 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day took place on April 11 with the Boston Red Sox and Washington Senators playing, while National League Opening Day took place the following day.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 25 and featured all sixteen teams, continuing the trend which began with the 1930 season.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between September 28 and October 2.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (3 in AL, 2 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 28 and ended on October 2 with the New York Yankees sweeping the Chicago Cubs in the 1932 World Series in four games.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] Across 77 homes games, the Boston Red Sox played their Tuesday, April 19 doubleheader against the New York Yankees and their first four of their 16 Sunday games at the Boston Braves home field of Braves Field (the remaining 71 home games were played at Fenway Park).
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last of four consecutive season playing some (mostly Sunday) games at Braves Field.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The stadium was previously home of the single-season National Football League team that was also named the Cleveland Indians.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the 1st of 12 seasons since that saw the Indians play at both venues, occurring again in every season from 1936 to 1946.
[src:arky-vaughan/1932-major-league-baseball-season] To this point, the Indians played all 32 of their seasons since their inaugural 1901 season at League Park.
[src:arky-vaughan/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1934 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the second edition of the mid-summer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:arky-vaughan/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It was held on July 10 in Manhattan, New York City, at the Polo Grounds, the home of the New York Giants of the National League, the defending World Series champions.
[src:arky-vaughan/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League won 9–7, and every starter on both teams except Wally Berger was later inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:arky-vaughan/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game is well known among baseball historians for the performance of NL starting pitcher Carl Hubbell of the host Giants.
[src:arky-vaughan/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] After allowing the first two batters to reach base on a single and a base on balls, Hubbell struck out five of the game's best hitters – Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Jimmie Foxx, Al Simmons, and Joe Cronin – in succession, setting a longstanding All-Star Game record for consecutive strikeouts.
[src:arky-vaughan/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Trailing 4–2, the American League scored six times in the top of the fifth inning to take the lead for good.
[src:arky-vaughan/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The teams combined for sixteen runs on 22 hits; the two home runs were hit early in the game by the NL (Frankie Frisch, Joe Medwick), both with the St.
[src:arky-vaughan/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis Cardinals, the World Series champions later that year.
[src:arky-vaughan/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Players in *italics* have since been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:arky-vaughan/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Cy Pfirman, NL (home), Brick Owens, AL (first base), Dolly Stark, NL (second base), George Moriarty, AL (third base); the umpires rotated positions clockwise in the middle of the fifth inning, with Owens moving behind the plate.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1941 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the ninth playing of the mid-summer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 8, 1941, at Briggs Stadium in Detroit, Michigan, the home of the Detroit Tigers of the American League.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League defeated the National League, 7–5.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With the NL leading 5–4, two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning, and Joe Gordon and Joe DiMaggio of the New York Yankees on base; Ted Williams of the Boston Red Sox hit a walk-off home run off of Claude Passeau of the Chicago Cubs to win it for the AL.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Prior to Williams' at-bat DiMaggio hit a potential game-ending double play groundball.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] However, Billy Herman’s relay throw pulled first baseman Frank McCormick off the bag, thus extending the game and setting up Williams' at-bat.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the end, the AL's dramatic 7–5 walk-off win overshadowed two home runs hit by Pittsburgh Pirates shortstop Arky Vaughan, which had given the NL 3–2 and 5–2 leads in the seventh and eighth innings, respectively.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires changed assignments in the middle of the fifth inning – Summers and Pinelli swapped positions, also Jorda and Grieve swapped positions.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Bob Feller (Cleveland, AL) and Whit Wyatt (Brooklyn, NL) pitched three and two scoreless innings, respectively, to start the game.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Neither team put a runner in scoring position until the fourth inning, when doubles by Cecil Travis (Washington) and Ted Williams off Paul Derringer (Cincinnati) put the AL ahead 1–0.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Bucky Waters (Cincinnati) led off the sixth inning with a double.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] A bunt by Stan Hack (Chicago Cubs) moved Waters to third and a sacrifice fly by Terry Moore (St.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL answered in the bottom half of the same inning when Cleveland shortstop Lou Boudreau (who had entered the game for Joe Cronin) singled home Joe DiMaggio for a 2–1 AL lead.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The top halves of the seventh and eighth innings saw the heroics of Arky Vaughan, who hit a two-run home run in each to also score two St.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis Cardinals players: Enos Slaughter, who had opened the seventh inning with a single, and Johnny Mize, who had preceded Vaughan's round-tripper in the eighth with a one-out double.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With the score now 5–2 in favor of the National League the first pair of brothers to ever appear together in an All-Star Game cut into the NL lead, when Dom DiMaggio – in his first plate appearance of the game – singled home Joe after his one-out double.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the ninth inning, White Sox pitcher Eddie Smith, who had given up one of Vaughan's home runs, retired the NL in order in his second inning of work.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] One of the three NL hitters to step to the plate that half-inning was pitcher Claude Passeau, who – with his team leading 5–3 – was not pulled for a pinch hitter, and thus returned to the mound in the bottom of the ninth for his third inning of work.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With one out in the bottom of the ninth, three consecutive AL batters reached base, putting the tying and go-ahead runs on base and bringing Joe DiMaggio to the plate.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The “Yankee Clipper” then hit what some sources describe as a routine double-play groundball, which would have ended the ballgame.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] However, the relay throw from second to first by Billy Herman pulled first baseman Frank McCormick off the bag and extended the game.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With the NL still leading 5–4 (a run had scored on DiMaggio's groundout), the AL now had the tying run on third and the winning run on first.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Not electing to walk Ted Williams, which would have advanced the winning run to second base and brought Dom DiMaggio to the plate, NL manager Bill McKechnie let Passeau pitch to Williams.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With the count two balls and one strike Williams hit a three-run home run off the third deck of the right field stands of Detroit's Briggs Stadium for a 7–5 American League victory.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The 1941 All-Star Game took place in the midst of Joe DiMaggio’s 56-game hitting streak (but did not count towards it, as the All-Star Game is regarded as an exhibition game).
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] DiMaggio had equaled the all-time record of 44 games, set by Willie Keeler in 1897, seven days prior to the All-Star Game and broken it the day after that (July 1 and 2, respectively).
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The streak would end nine days after the All-Star Game, when DiMaggio went hitless on July 17 against the Cleveland Indians.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Ted Williams, whose batting average was at .405 at the time of the All-Star Game, would even slightly improve on that hitting pace for the rest of the season and end the 1941 campaign at .406, making him the last hitter to reach the .400 mark for a season.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The 1941 Major League Baseball season, of which the All-Star Game marked the midway point, was the last played prior to the United States' entry into World War II.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The juxtaposition of that memorable season taking place with the war looming is illustrated in the 1991 book *Baseball in ’41* by renowned sportswriter Robert Creamer.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Although the Major League season and the World Series would continue to be played during the war years, the All-Star Game was cancelled in 1945 due to wartime travel restrictions.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] The **1941 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1941.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 28, with the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 38th World Series on October 1 and ended with Game 5 on October 6.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] The Yankees defeated the Dodgers, four games to one, capturing their ninth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1939.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first Subway Series World Series to feature the Dodgers (the previous five featured the New York Giants).
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Cincinnati Reds from the 1940 season.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] The ninth All-Star Game was held on July 8 at Briggs Stadium in Detroit, Michigan, home of the Detroit Tigers.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Bees reverted their nickname to the "Braves" on April 29, the name they had prior to the 1936 season.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] In addition to a five-game World Series between New York City teams, highlights of the season included Ted Williams batting .406, and Joe DiMaggio having a 56-game hitting streak; it has been called the "best baseball season ever".
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] The 1941 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day took place on April 14 with a game between the New York Yankees and Washington Senators, while National League Opening Day took place on the following day, featuring all eight teams.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season since 1939 that both leagues opened on different days.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 28 and featured all sixteen teams, continuing the trend since the previous season.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 1 and October 6.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] 13 tie games (6 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 6 with the New York Yankees defeating the Brooklyn Dodgers in the 1941 World Series in five games.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] Over 77 home games, the Cleveland Indians played 45 games at League Park and 32 games at Cleveland Stadium.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] All Wednesday home games took place at League Park.
[src:arky-vaughan/1941-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the 7th of 12 seasons since 1932 that saw the Indians play at both venues, and was the last season which saw the majority of home games at League Park.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1942 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the tenth playing of the midsummer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 6, 1942, at Polo Grounds in New York City the home of the New York Giants of the National League.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the American League defeating the National League 3–1.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] While the game had been scheduled for a twilight start at 6:30 p.m.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] EWT, rain delayed the first pitch for an hour, leading to the first All-Star contest played entirely under the lights; the two-hour, seven-minute game ended just ahead of a 9:30 p.m. blackout curfew in New York.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] One night later, the American League All-Stars traveled to Cleveland Municipal Stadium in Cleveland, Ohio, to play a special benefit game against a team of players from the U.S.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The contest, which the American Leaguers won 5–0, attracted a crowd of 62,094 and netted $70,000 for the Army Emergency Relief Fund and the Navy Relief Society.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Mutual Radio broadcast the second game, with Bob Elson, Waite Hoyt, and Jack Graney announcing.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires changed assignments in the middle of the fifth inning – Ballanfant and McGowan swapped positions, also Stewart and Barlick swapped positions.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The **1942 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1942.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 27, with the St.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 39th World Series on September 30 and ended with Game 5 on October 5.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] In the third iteration of this World Series matchup, the Cardinals defeated the Yankees, four games to one, capturing their fourth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1934.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Yankees from the 1941 season.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The 10th All-Star Game was played on July 6 at the Polo Grounds in New York, New York, home of the New York Giants.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League, the Brooklyn Dodgers had a record of 104–50, but finished two games behind the Cardinals; the Dodgers tied the 1909 Chicago Cubs, who had a record of 104–49, for the most wins in an MLB regular season without reaching the postseason.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics set a record for the fewest runs batted in during a season, with only 354.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns nearly moved to Los Angeles, California for the start of the 1942 season.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] During the 1941 Winter Meetings in Chicago, Illinois, a vote was scheduled for the morning of December 8, and was expected to be approved.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] However, due to the attack on Pearl Harbor by Japan the previous day (and subsequent entry of the United States into World War II), when it came time to vote, all teams (including the Browns) unanimously voted against the move.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The team would eventually leave for Baltimore, Maryland in 1954 where they remain today as the Baltimore Orioles, while Los Angeles would eventually get a major league team in 1958 when the Dodgers moved from Brooklyn, New York.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The 1942 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 16, featured all sixteen teams, the first since the 1940 season.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 27 and featured ten teams.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between September 30 and October 5.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] 9 tie games (2 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 30 and ended on October 5 with the St.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals defeating the New York Yankees in the 1942 World Series in five games.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Over 80 home games, the Cleveland Indians played 46 games at Cleveland Stadium and 34 games at League Park.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] All Thursday home games took place at League Park.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the 8th of 12 seasons since 1932 that saw the Indians play at both venues.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Following the reversion of the Boston Bees name to Boston Braves the previous season, National League Park's name was also reverted, to Braves Field.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds re-entered Willard Hershberger's No.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] 5 into circulation, only two years after his number was retired.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first number to be de-retired by any team in MLB.
[src:arky-vaughan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] His number would later be re-retired to honor Johnny Bench in 1984.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The **1943 major league baseball season** began on April 20, 1943.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 3, with the St.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 40th World Series on October 5 and ended with Game 5 on October 11.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] In the fourth iteration of this World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), the Yankees defeated the Cardinals, four games to one, capturing their tenth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1941.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The 11th All-Star Game was held on July 13 at the Shibe Park in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, hosted by the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] This was also the first All-Star Game held at night.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] In order to conserve rail transport during World War II, the 1943 spring training sites was limited to an area east of the Mississippi River and north of the Ohio River.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] Spring training sites included the Chicago White Sox in French Lick, Indiana; the Washington Senators in College Park, Maryland; and the Yankees in Asbury Park, New Jersey.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The 1943 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day took place on April 20 with a game between the Philadelphia Athletics and Washington Senators, while National League Opening Day took place on the following day, featuring four teams.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season since 1941 that both leagues opened on different days.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 3, which saw all sixteen teams play, also the first time since 1941.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 5 and October 11.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] 11 tie games (4 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 5 and ended on October 11 with the New York Yankees defeating the St.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals in the 1943 World Series in five games.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] Over 77 home games, the Cleveland Indians played 48 games at Cleveland Stadium and 29 games at League Park.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] All Sunday home games took place at Cleveland Stadium.
[src:arky-vaughan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the 9th of 12 seasons since 1932 that saw the Indians play at both venues.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Born in Clifty, Arkansas, Vaughan got his nickname early in life, despite leaving Arkansas before his first birthday.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Vaughan made his professional debut in 1931 at age 19 for the minor league Wichita Aviators of the Western League, where he hit .338 with 21 home runs.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] When the Aviators became affiliated with the Chicago Cubs after the season, Vaughan was acquired by the Tulsa Oilers, who were affiliated with the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] On April 7, 1932, Vaughan was acquired from the Oilers by the Pirates.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Vaughan began the 1932 season as the backup to the Pirates' starting shortstop, Tommy Thevenow.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Through the first 13 games of the season, Vaughan appeared only twice, once as a late-game replacement for Thevenow and once as a pinch-hitter.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] However, Thevenow was still suffering the effects of a season-ending ankle injury he had suffered in 1931, which opened up the door for Vaughan to take over the job.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] When Thevenow returned at the end of May after missing a month, he found himself in a reserve role.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Vaughan, who was the youngest player in the National League in 1932, wound up playing 129 games overall that year, all but one at shortstop.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] He finished with a .318 batting average and 61 runs batted in (RBIs) in his rookie season.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] His defense was a bit shaky, though, as he led the league in errors with 46.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] His year was impressive enough to garner a modicum of support for Most Valuable Player, finishing 23rd in the voting.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Vaughan solidified his position as the Pirates' starting shortstop in 1933.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Improving on almost all of his offensive statistics, Vaughan played in 152 games, batting .314 with 97 RBI, seventh- and fifth-best in the NL respectively.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] He finished in the league top five in on-base percentage (.388, 3rd), slugging percentage (.478, 5th) and walks (64, 4th).
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Although he led the league in errors again with an identical 46 to the previous year, due to his increased playing time his fielding percentage improved a bit from .934 to .945.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] For the second straight year, he finished 23rd in the MVP voting.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Vaughan took his game up another notch in 1934.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] While finishing fourth in the race for the batting title at .333, he led the league in OBP at .431, helped by his league-leading walk total of 94.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Although he dropped from fifth to sixth in slugging, the raw number improved to .511.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] His performance earned him a spot on the NL All-Star team, the first of what would be nine straight selections.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] His defense continued to improve as well, as his error total dropped to 41, no longer the most in the league, and his fielding percentage rose again to .951.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] For the third straight year, he finished 23rd in the MVP voting.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] In 1935, Vaughan had what is universally recognized as his best season.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Vaughan not only posted career bests in the three Triple Crown categories, he led all of baseball with a .385 average, a .491 on-base percentage, and a 1.098 OPS.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] His 190 Adjusted OPS as of 2011 still ranks as one of the top 100 single-season scores of all time.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] His .607 slugging percentage led the NL, as did his 97 walks.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] His 19 home runs were eighth in the league, his only time in the top ten, and his 99 RBI were sixth.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] He also earned the first of his six starts in the All-Star Game.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Defensively, he finished in the top half of the league in fielding percentage for the first time while finishing second in both putouts and assists.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Although he was third in National League MVP voting behind Gabby Hartnett and Dizzy Dean, he was named Player of the Year by The Sporting News.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] The season has been called the best ever by a shortstop other than Honus Wagner.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Over the next six seasons, Vaughan continued to be one of the best-hitting shortstops in the game, batting over .300 in every season, and regularly being at or near the top of the league in most offensive categories.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] By the time Vaughan reached the age of 25, he had accumulated 1,057 hits, the 18th highest total for a 25-year-old in MLB history.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] He also continued to improve defensively, as he led the league in total chances in 1938–39 while finishing in the top three in fielding percentage four times.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] He again finished third in the MVP voting in 1938, when the Pirates finished second and had their best record during his tenure with the team.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] In 1940, Vaughan was appointed team captain by new manager Frankie Frisch.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Although he led the league in runs scored and triples again, he slumped to a career-low .300 batting average.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] This prompted Frisch to replace Vaughan as starting shortstop with Alf Anderson to start the 1941 season.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] However, Anderson didn't hit, and Vaughan was quickly back in the starting lineup.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] In the 1941 All-Star Game, Vaughan hit two home runs, but was upstaged by a ninth-inning, three-run homer by American Leaguer Ted Williams.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Vaughan finished the year batting .316 in 106 games.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] That would be his last year with the Pirates who wouldn't see a star as bright as Vaughan for almost two decades.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] The fans were outraged at his trade to Brooklyn and his mysterious death years later helped coin the phrase "The Ghost of Arky" when times got tough.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] On December 12, 1941, after a decade as the Pirates' starting shortstop, Vaughan was traded to the Brooklyn Dodgers for Pete Coscarart, Luke Hamlin, Babe Phelps, and Jimmy Wasdell.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] It is believed that this trade was in part prompted due to bad feelings between Vaughan and Frisch.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Since Pee Wee Reese was already at shortstop for the Dodgers, the plan was to move Vaughan to third base.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Vaughan's tenure with the Dodgers got off to a rough start, as he failed to hit .300 for the first time in his career, finishing at .277 with just two home runs.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] He also established new lows in several other categories, including a career-worst .348 OBP.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] He still managed to make the All-Star team as the starter at third base, and actually finished third in the league in fielding percentage, but the season was a disappointment overall.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] With Reese drafted into World War II, Vaughan was moved back to shortstop in 1943.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] He rebounded on offense, raising his average over .300 once again at .305 and leading the league in runs scored and, for the first and only time, stolen bases with 20.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] However, the season was marred by an incident that would nearly lead to the end of Vaughan's career.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] On July 10, temperamental manager Leo Durocher suspended pitcher Bobo Newsom for insubordination after Newsom complained about catcher Bobby Bragan dropping a third strike.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Durocher subsequently fed false claims to the press that Newsom had thrown an illegal spitball after being instructed not to.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] According to teammate Billy Herman, after reading Durocher's comments about Newsom, Vaughan went into the manager's office, took off his uniform, and "threw it in Durocher's face".
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] After the season, Vaughan left the team, retiring to his ranch.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] He went on to sit out the next three years.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] After Durocher was suspended before the 1947 season, Vaughan decided to try a comeback.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Serving as something of a utility player, Vaughan played in 64 games and batted .325.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] He played in his only World Series that season, which the Dodgers lost to the New York Yankees.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Vaughan appeared in three games in the 1947 World Series, all as a pinch hitter, reaching base twice on a walk and a double.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Even with Durocher's suspension over, Vaughan returned to the Dodgers in a similar capacity in 1948.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] However, after batting a career-low .244 in 65 games, he was released at the end of the season.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] He played the 1949 season with Pacific Coast League's San Francisco Seals before retiring for good.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Vaughan retired with 1,173 runs scored, 96 home runs, 926 RBI, 118 steals, a .318 batting average, .406 on-base percentage and .453 slugging percentage.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] As of 2019, his .385 batting average, .491 OBP, and 1.098 OPS in 1935 are all Pittsburgh team records, and the batting average is a 20th-century record for National League shortstops.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Vaughan is the 26th greatest non-pitcher in major league history, according to win shares.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] He hit for the cycle twice in his career as a member of the Pirates.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] In 14 seasons, he hit .300 or better 12 times, only missing the mark in 1942 and 1948.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] In 1981, Lawrence Ritter and Donald Honig included Vaughan in their book *The 100 Greatest Baseball Players of All Time*.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] In his *New Historical Baseball Abstract*, published in 2001, Bill James rated Vaughan as the second-best shortstop in major league history, behind fellow Pirate and mentor Honus Wagner.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] In his 2021 book, *The Baseball 100*, Joe Posnanski places Vaughan at number 61 on a list of the 100 all-time greatest baseball players.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Posnanski called Vaughan "the least-known great Major League Baseball player," stating: "He was so quiet and modest.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] He was not colorful in the ways that entertain sportswriters.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Vaughan married his wife, Margaret, in 1931, and they had four children.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] After leaving the Seals, Vaughan bought a ranch in Eagleville, California, where he retired to fish, hunt, and tend cattle.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] On August 30, 1952, Vaughan was fishing in nearby Lost Lake, with his friend Bill Wimer.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] According to a witness, Wimer stood up in the boat, causing it to capsize, and both men drowned.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] In Joe Posnanski's characterization of the incident, an eyewitness saw Vaughan swim back to assist his companion.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Their bodies were recovered the next day.
[src:arky-vaughan/arky-vaughan] Vaughan's nephew Glenn Vaughan had a brief major league career with the Houston Colt .45s in 1963.
